{{other uses|Aspirator (disambiguation)}}

{{expert needed|Medicine|date=September 2018}}
{{Wikibooks|Medical Suction Machines}}

[[File:Potains-aspirator.png|thumb|200px|Potain's aspirator]]
A medical '''aspirator''' is a suction machine used to remove [[mucus]], [[blood]], and other bodily fluids from a patient. They can be used during surgical procedures but an operating theater is generally equipped with a central system of vacuum tubes.<ref>{{cite web |title=Aspirator |url=http://www.who.int/medical_devices/innovation/aspirator.pdf |website=Core Medical Equipment |accessdate=19 September 2018}}</ref> Most aspirators are therefore portable, for use in [[ambulance]]s and [[nursing home]]s, and can run on AC/DC or battery power. They consist of a vacuum pump, a
vacuum regulator and gauge, a collection canister, and sometimes a
bacterial filter. Plastic tubing is used to continuously draw fluid into the collection canister.

In the past manually operated aspirators were used such as ''Potain's aspirator''.<ref>p. 97, Minor surgery, Henry R. Wharton, in [https://books.google.com/books?id=byqN9YXA9bkC ''System of surgery''], vol. II, Frederic S. Dennis and John S. Billings, eds., Philadelphia: Lea Brothers & Co., 1895.</ref>  [[File:Gomco4040Aspirator.jpg|thumb|The contemporary Gomco 4040 Aspirator]]

[[File:LaerdalPortableSuction.jpg|thumb|A Laerdal portable suction machine with battery and power cord.]]
