{{Infobox Company | name = GeoSmart (NZ) Ltd | logo = | type = Private | genre = | foundation = New Zealand (1977) | founder = | location_city = Auckland,Mairangi Bay | location_country = New Zealand | location = | locations = | area_served = Oceania | key_people = | industry = [[Location-based service]]s, [[Geographic information system]], [[GPS]], Cartography | products = SmartMap, SmartFind, Invite2GO | services = | market cap = | revenue = | operating_income = | net_income = | assets = | equity = | owner = | num_employees = | parent = | divisions = | subsid = | homepage = | footnotes = | intl = }}
'''GeoSmart (NZ) Ltd''' is a provider of location-based services, digital mapping data and images for the Oceania area, notably [[New Zealand]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mapscape.eu/index.php?option=com_weblinks&catid=9&Itemid=8|title=Content Suppliers|publisher=[[Mapscape BV]]|accessdate=2008-08-12|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713052849/http://www.mapscape.eu/index.php?option=com_weblinks&catid=9&Itemid=8|archivedate=2011-07-13|df=}}</ref> The company is one of only a handful of global companies producing digital maps for use in [[GPS]] applications.
Companies such as [[TomTom]] and [[Navman]], use mapping data from GeoSmart on their popular handheld GPS devices,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/section/story.cfm?c_id=5&objectid=10470546|title=Dutch GPS maker out to navigate NZ market|publisher=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|author=Peter Griffin|date=2007-10-18|accessdate=2008-08-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/section/story.cfm?c_id=5&objectid=10344997|title=Our turn for new Navman|publisher=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|author=Peter Griffin|date=2007-10-18|accessdate=2005-09-11}}</ref> as do motor manufacturers such as [[BMW]].<ref>{{cite news|title=BMW points NZ in the right direction|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/section/story.cfm?c_id=5&objectid=3576579|date=2004-07-06|accessdate=2008-08-12|author=Paul Brislen|work=The New Zealand Herald}}</ref> The company also provides mapping data via [[web service]]s, with applications such as a website that allows users to send custom invitations that include mapping directions for guests <ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/section/story.cfm?c_id=5&objectid=10415265|title=Geosmart gets ready to party|date=2006-12-14|accessdate=2008-08-12|publisher=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|author=Peter Griffin}}</ref> as well as providing the mapping interface on [[New Zealand Automobile Association]] website.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/section/1/story.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10355323|title=Online service allows travellers to customise maps |date=2005-11-15|accessdate=2008-08-12|publisher=[[The New Zealand Herald]]}}</ref>
In 2008, GeoSmart launched the RAPIDcV mapping car, which is an ongoing program to redrive all of New Zealand. This is to enhance the car navigation database used by brands including Navman, TomTom, Nav N Go, Siemens VDO and Horizon.{{Fact|date=April 2009}} The RAPIDcV (Road attributes, [[point of interest|points of interest]], imagery data capture vehicle) uses technology to capture the road centreline of all of New Zealand's roads to an accuracy of 0.15 metres.<ref>{{cite news|title=GeoSmart's RAPIDcV vehicle sets mapping in motion |url=http://www.geosmart.co.nz/news/newsletters/_details/id_94/welcome_to_smartnews.html?Return=news%2Fnewsletters}}</ref> It does this with a number of technologies including [[Inertial navigation system|inertial]] measurement unit (IMU) that uses [[gyroscope]]s and [[accelerometer]]s. This technology compensates for situations where the traditional [[differential GPS]] accuracy is lost when the satellite signal is poor, such as behind volcanic hill shadows, dense forest canopies and high rise urban areas. It has a number of cameras on board capturing lane information, street signs, turn restrictions and points of interest to enhance and keep up to date GeoSmart's car navigation and web mapping products. It is also taking a 360 degree [[Panoramic photography|panoramic image]] every 50 metres. In order to support truck navigation as well as multi mode navigation it is collecting information on the incline and [[Cant (road/rail)|camber]] of each corner, a feature which is used for truck safety warnings in [[fleet management system]]s.{{Fact|date=April 2009}}
